At least 38 people have been killed after a gold mine collapsed in West Kordofan State in southern Sudan, a government agency said in a statement.  "The General Manager of the Sudanese Mineral Resources Company Limited eulogises the death of 38 miners who died as a result of the collapse of Umm Draisaya mine," the statement read.  The collapsed gold mine lies near El Nuhud town in West Kordofan State, 500km west of Sudan's capital Khartoum.Â   The government of West Kordofan State and the state's security committee previously issued a decision to close the mine.  By Reuters | 1 day ago By Agencies and Mireri Junior | 2 days ago By Standard Reporter | 3 days ago By Reuters | 3 days ago Enjoy unlimited access to The Standard website at a 50% discount on the yearly plan.